📋 USPS IVS — Consolidated Issue Profile (Source of Truth)

1. Issue Definition
Problem A — Alternating Pass/Fail on ConfirmPasscode (Primary Bug)
Symptom: When a user goes through the remote proofing flow (Check Device → Verify Phone → Confirm Passcode), the ConfirmPasscode call alternates between 200 OK (success) and 400 Bad Request (failure) on successive attempts. The failure is not tied to user input — a correct passcode sometimes succeeds, sometimes fails, depending purely on which backend server handles the request.
Additional observation: The 400 response also manifests when a wrong passcode is entered, which corrupts the session state such that even a subsequently correct passcode fails. This is a distinct but related symptom of the same root cause.
Confirmed environments:
	•	Happening in SIT (System Integration Testing) with two servers active
	•	Not consistently reproducible in CAT (Certification/Acceptance Testing) or PROD — because those environments may route to a single server for that sponsor/supplier combination at a given time
	•	The issue disappears entirely when testing against a single server by direct IP address — this is the critical diagnostic clue
Root Cause (already identified from prior analysis): This is a stateful dependency hidden in a nominally stateless REST API, caused by round-robin load balancing without session affinity. verifyPhone() writes verification state on Server BC4. confirmPasscode() routes to Server BC5 via round-robin, which re-queries the database independently and receives null because the transaction from BC4 hasn’t committed/propagated yet. The absence of JSESSIONID cookie propagation prevents WebSphere session affinity from engaging.

Problem B — Database Row Lock / Table Contention (Secondary Bug)
Symptom: In production, during high-volume CoA (Change of Address) traffic, all transactions begin timing out. No users can progress through OTP or SMFA verification. The system appears frozen from the user’s perspective.
Specific behavior observed:
	•	504 Gateway Timeout responses
	•	Read timeout errors logged against the verifyPhone endpoint
	•	Database queries show multiple sessions blocked by a single session holding a row lock
	•	Once the blocking session commits, the counters resume incrementing and traffic flows again — exactly mirroring what was reproduced in the load test
Root Cause (confirmed by load test): The RPTV_ATTEMPTS table (or equivalent supplier routing table) has two rows for CoA’s split supplier configuration (e.g., 60% LexisNexis / 40% Equifax). Every incoming transaction must UPDATE one of these rows to increment the attempt counter before routing to a supplier. Under high concurrency, Oracle row-level locks cause queued blocking — each transaction waits for the previous one to commit before it can update the same row. With CoA’s volume, the queue grows large enough to cascade into timeouts.

