5. Key Diagnostic Tests Performed
Load Test (DB Lock Reproduction):
	•	Palin executed an uncommitted UPDATE statement on the supplier routing table rows
	•	Mohammed ran a multi-user load test simultaneously
	•	Result: 504s appeared within seconds; Oracle blocker query confirmed session 535 was blocking all others
	•	Upon COMMIT by Palin: counters resumed, 200 OK responses returned — lock confirmed as root cause of prod outage
Single-Server Test (Alternating Issue isolation):
	•	Emma tested confirmPasscode using a direct server IP (bypassing load balancer)
	•	Result: consistent 200 OK — no alternating
	•	Two-server test via load balancer: alternating 200/400 resumed
	•	Conclusion: issue is strictly load-balancer/session-affinity related, not a code logic bug
100% Supplier Configuration Test:
	•	Switching either supplier to 100% stops all UPDATE writes to the attempt table
	•	No writes → no row locks → no contention
	•	This is a workaround, not a fix — it sidesteps the contention by eliminating the split routing calculation entirely

6. Proposed Fixes (from meetings)
Fix A — Alternating Issue (confirmPasscode)
Modify checkPhoneVerified() in RemoteSupportServiceImpl to accept the already-fetched RpPhoneVerification object rather than re-querying the database. Update call sites in both confirmPasscode() and requestPasscode(). Restore the commented-out OTP supplier validation guard. This eliminates the cross-server DB re-query that causes the null result.
Fix B — DB Lock Contention (Emer/Emma’s Proposal)
Replace the UPDATE pattern on RPTV_ATTEMPTS with an INSERT-only approach using a new table RPPV_SUPPLIER_SELECTION. Each transaction inserts a new row rather than updating a shared row. The algorithm determines the next supplier by reading the latest inserted record and computing the next selection, avoiding Oracle row-level locks entirely. Truncate/reset the table when the cycle completes.
Alternative approaches discussed (not yet implemented):
	•	In-memory/cache-based counter (e.g., Redis) — flagged as technology compliance risk on WebSphere
	•	Hard-coding percentages in application code and computing in-memory — discussed but not evaluated
	•	Separate table per sponsor — ruled out; same locking problem persists

